  "texts": [
    "The most popular option was to have a university wide policy which made it clear when they are or are not appropriate to use, with 41.1% of respondents selecting this option (Table 9).",
    "Of the 46 respondents who selected 'Other' the majority of students suggested that there be limitations put in place rather than an outright ban (18/46): \"Educate people on how the AI tools can be used in ways other than to simply cheat, for example to improve revision, speed up the writing process, or help with \"I believe these technologies need to be embraced in an academic setting and adopted asap.",
    "The way the university should handle these technologies should be a mixture of the options provided in this survey… For example it may be appropriate for one department to allow AI to help with research, as long as it's referenced; for other departments it may be deemed inappropriate for it to be used and thus banned. \"",
    "\"I have found that assistive technologies can be really helpful without necessarily encroaching upon my academic integrity, for example I use it to quickly recall an obscure formula that would take me a while to find on the internet while doing problems.",
    "But when it becomes evident (using AI detectors) that submitted work is predominantly the work of the computer and not the student, measures and sanctions should be taken... \""
